A Cox proportional hazards model was used to assess the protective efficacy of the experimental vaccine against symptomatic COVID-19 after vaccination for 7 days. The model incorporated person-years of exposure as the dependent variable, and age (18-59 years, ≥60 years), last dose vaccine type (inactivated vaccines, non-inactivated vaccines), and group as fixed effects. The vaccine's protective rate and its 95% confidence interval were calculated based on the model. For events with overlapping time, the Efron method was employed. If the model encountered convergence issues, step one would be to remove the stratification factor of the last dose vaccine type, and then further remove the age stratification factor if convergence issues persisted.

The primary endpoint person-years of exposure was calculated as (effective case monitoring period observation termination/lost time - vaccination time -14)/365.25. Termination/lost time was determined as follows:
1. For symptomatic individuals diagnosed with COVID-19 before the data analysis cut-off date, termination time was the date of first symptom onset;
2. For those with positive rapid antigen and/or RT-PCR test results after vaccination but not diagnosed with the targeted event, the earliest sampling date for the positive results was used;
3. For those with negative rapid antigen and RT-PCR tests without a diagnosis of the targeted event, lost time was the last follow-up date;
4. For those who received other COVID-19 vaccines before the data analysis cut-off date, lost time was the first vaccine administration date. Targeted events diagnosed after other vaccines were not included in case counts.

A Kaplan-Meier curve of symptomatic COVID-19 incidence rates after 7 days of vaccination was drawn. The primary protective efficacy analysis was based on mFAS, PPS, and PPE populations, with results for PPE as the main analysis results. Furthermore, the following sensitivity analyses for primary protective efficacy were conducted:

Sensitivity analysis 1 (vaccine protective rate analysis based on exact Poisson regression model): An exact Poisson regression model was used to assess the protective efficacy of the experimental vaccine against symptomatic COVID-19 after 7 days of vaccination. The model estimated the vaccine protective rate based on person-year incidence rates and its 95% confidence interval. The Poisson regression model used the number of illness cases as the dependent variable, age (18-59 years, ≥60 years), last dose vaccine type (inactivated vaccines, non-inactivated vaccines), and group as fixed effects. The offset was the subject exposure person-years, with a log link function.

Sensitivity analysis 2 (vaccine protective rate analysis based on incidence rates): The incidence rates of symptomatic COVID-19 and their Clopper-Pearson 95% confidence intervals were calculated for both the experimental and control groups after 7 days of vaccination. CMH "χ" ^ "2" tests considering random stratification factors were used to assess group differences. The vaccine's protective rate and its 95% confidence interval were calculated.

Sensitivity analysis 3 (vaccine protective rate analysis based on the Cox model without considering stratification factors): A Cox proportional hazards model was used to assess the protective efficacy of the experimental vaccine against symptomatic COVID-19 after 7 days of vaccination. The model incorporated person-years of exposure as the dependent variable and group as a fixed effect. The vaccine's protective rate and its 95% confidence interval were calculated based on the model.

